  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds appear legitimate by integrating them into the economy.\n\nMoney laundering is a criminal offense in virtually every country and is subject to severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. Various international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), work to combat money laundering by setting global standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures. Additionally, many countries have established specific laws and agencies to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.",
